## Best Practices

### DO ✅

```ruby
# Validate at model level (not just client-side)
validates :email, presence: true

# Use database constraints for critical validations
# Migration:
add_index :users, :email, unique: true
# Model:
validates :email, uniqueness: true

# Use presence for required fields
validates :title, :body, presence: true

# Use format for structured data
validates :email, format: { with: EMAIL_REGEX }

# Use numericality for numbers
validates :age, numericality: { greater_than: 0 }

# Use inclusion for enums/constants
validates :status, inclusion: { in: STATUSES }

# Keep error messages user-friendly
validates :email, presence: { message: "is required" }

# Use conditional validations
validates :password, presence: true, on: :create

# Test validations thoroughly
# test/models/user_test.rb
test "should not save user without email" do
  user = User.new
  assert_not user.save
end
```

### DON'T ❌

```ruby
# Don't rely only on client-side validation
# Always validate server-side

# Don't use presence for boolean fields
validates :published, presence: true  # Bad! false is "blank"
validates :published, inclusion: { in: [true, false] }  # Good!

# Don't forget database indexes for uniqueness
validates :email, uniqueness: true  # Without index, race condition possible!

# Don't validate in controllers
# Validate in models instead

# Don't skip validations without good reason
article.save(validate: false)  # Dangerous!

# Don't use update_attribute in production
article.update_attribute(:title, "New")  # Skips validations!
article.update(title: "New")  # Runs validations (good!)

# Don't duplicate validation logic
# DRY: Define once in model, reuse everywhere

# Don't forget to test edge cases
# Test nil, blank, invalid format, etc.
```

